---
intent: >
  Build the IntentTreeSection component — a static monospace folder-tree
  diagram with inline annotations showing how .aide specs cascade through
  a content-pipeline example application — and wire it into the LandingPage
  orchestrator as beat 5 between VsRulesPacks and HallucinationEvidence.
---

## Plan

### 1. Create the IntentTreeSection component

Read: `coding-playbook/client/components`, `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions`

- [x] Create `src/components/LandingPage/IntentTreeSection/index.tsx`.
- [x] Default export: `IntentTreeSection`, arrow function component, no props.
- [x] JSDoc: one line — "Static folder-tree diagram showing cascading .aide
      intent specs through an example content-pipeline application."
- [x] Outer element: `<section className="w-full py-16 px-4 border-t border-zinc-800">`
      — matches VsRulesPacks, HallucinationEvidence, CostStrip section wrappers.
- [x] Inner container: `<div className="max-w-2xl mx-auto flex flex-col gap-6">`
      — matches sibling beat sections.
- [x] Heading block (same pattern as VsRulesPacks/HallucinationEvidence):
      - `<h2 className="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-100">` with text:
        "Intent cascades through the project tree"
      - No subtitle `<p>` below the heading. The spec explicitly forbids
        explanatory prose between the heading and the diagram — the diagram
        is self-explanatory via its annotations.
- [x] Tree diagram container: style the outer wrapper to match the shared
      `CodeBlock` visual treatment — `rounded-lg bg-zinc-900 border border-zinc-800`.
      Add inner padding `p-4`. Do NOT reuse the shared `CodeBlock` component
      because it renders a plain string; the tree needs per-line styling to
      visually distinguish `.aide` annotation lines from plain file lines.
- [x] Render the tree as a `<pre>` with `className="text-sm font-mono leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"`.
      Inside the `<pre>`, render each line of the tree as its own element so
      annotations can be styled differently from file/folder names.
- [x] Tree data representation: define the tree as an array of objects at the
      top of the file (above the component, below imports). Each object has:
      `text` (the folder/file portion including box-drawing characters) and
      an optional `annotation` (the right-aligned description). This keeps the
      data declarative and the rendering logic minimal. Approximately 18 lines
      per the spec's good example.
- [x] Tree content — use the exact content-pipeline example from the spec's
      Good Examples section. The domain is `content-pipeline/` with modules
      `ingest/`, `transform/`, `publish/` and a submodule `parseFeed/` under
      ingest. The helper `normalize/` has no `.aide` spec. Annotations use the
      word "narrows" to reinforce the cascade concept.
- [x] Styling per line:
      - Tree structure characters and folder/file names: `text-zinc-400` (muted).
      - `.aide` and `intent.aide` file names within the text portion: `text-zinc-200`
        (brighter than surrounding structure to draw the eye).
      - Annotation arrows and text (`<- ...`): `text-zinc-500` — visible but
        secondary to the tree structure. Use `text-emerald-500` or `text-zinc-500`
        for the arrow marker to create a subtle highlight consistent with the
        VsRulesPacks section's use of emerald for positive markers. Pick one:
        `text-zinc-500` for the arrow, keeping annotations understated as
        engineering documentation rather than marketing highlights.
      - The helper line `(helper - no spec)`: `text-zinc-600` — deliberately
        dimmer to show absence.
- [x] No interactivity, no animation, no click handlers, no hover effects.
      The spec explicitly forbids interactive tree behavior.
- [x] No copy button on this code block. Unlike the install JSON, the tree
      diagram is a visual artifact, not something the visitor pastes.

